==English==
===Etymology===
Spanish ''[[olla#Spanish|olla]],'' from Latin ''[[olla#Latin|olla]], [[aulla]];'' akin to the [[w:Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]] (''[[ukhā]]''), that is [[pot]], and probably to [[w:Gothic language|Gothic]] (''[[auhns''), [[oven]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'ɒlə/

===Noun===
{{en-noun|olla|ollas}}
# a cooking-pot or [[earthenware]] [[jar]] used in Spain and Spanish-speaking countries
#:*'''1992''': On top of the counter were three clay jars or '''ollas.'''  Two of them were empty but the third was covered with the tin lid from a [[lardpail]] and the [[lid]] was [[notch]]ed to [[accommodate]] the [[handle]] of an [[enamel#verb|enameled]] tin [[dipper]]. — [[w:Cormac McCarthy|Cormac McCarthy,]] ''All the Pretty Horses''
# A pot used for cooling [[water]] by [[evaporation]] in [[Latin America]].
# A [[cinerary]] [[urn]] in [[ancient]] [[Rome]].

